A Google I/O Idea
-----------------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/news/610508/google-i-o-2025-date =
) , in February:

Google=E2=80=99s next I/O developer conference will take place on May 20th =
and May 21st, the company announced today. The event will be =E2=80=9Copen =
to everyone online=E2=80=9D and will include =E2=80=9Clivestreamed keynotes=
 and sessions,=E2=80=9D according to an FAQ. Like past years, there will al=
so be an in-person component at the Shoreline Amphitheatre in Mountain View=
, California=E2=80=A6

The last Google I/O kicked off on May 14th, 2024. The event was packed with=
 a ton of announcements, including new Gemini AI features and models, the P=
roject Astra AI assistant, its Veo generative AI video model, and a big AI-=
focused overhaul for Google Search. The 2023 edition of I/O was filled with=
 AI news, too, but at that show, Google also announced the Pixel Fold, Pixe=
l Tablet, and Pixel 7A.

I was chatting with John Gruber after recording this morning's Dithering ( =
https://dithering.passport.online/member/episode/apples-identity-ai-crisis =
) , and he posited a very funny scenario: a Google executive takes the stag=
e, pulls out an Android phone, and says, "Google, when is my mom's flight l=
anding?"

That's in reference to this demo in last year's WWDC keynote:

( https://videopress.com/embed/SpcMjMRl?cover=3D1&autoPlay=3D0&controls=3D1=
&loop=3D0&muted=3D0&persistVolume=3D1&playsinline=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmeta=
data&useAverageColor=3D1&hd=3D0 )

What would make this potential I/O prank effective is if it works, live and=
 on-stage, not pre-recorded and (probably) doctored. It certainly seems pos=
sible, no? At a minimum, it surely seems more likely that Google could actu=
ally ship this feature.

